{
  "text": "In the back telemetry system, information about electrode impedances and receiver-stimulator status such as supply voltages and communication errors are fed back to the DSP chip using load modulation. To obtain information about electrode impedances, the receiver/stimulator samples the voltage difference between an active electrode and a reference electrode (the remote reference for monopolar stimulation or one of the two electrodes for bipolar stimulation). This sampled voltage is sent to the external speech processor via the back telemetry link. Electrode impedances are calculated in the external processor using this information. A voltage sampled at a node in the implant is converted to a proportional pulse duration, during which the quality factor of the receiver resonant circuit is reduced [CITATION_1] . This information is then read using the DSP chip. Alternatively, we could have included a separate inductive link for the backward communication using the FSK modulation, but this would have increased the complexity and size of the overall implant system.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "110583144"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "110583144": {
      "title": "Electronic design of a cochlear implant for multichannel high-rate pulsatile stimulation strategies",
      "abstract": "A new electronic design for an eight-channel cochlear implant for high-rate pulsatile stimulation strategies is presented. Symmetric biphasic current pulses can be generated up to a maximum pulse repetition rate of about 12 kpulses/s. The stimulation pulse amplitude can be selected within the range of 1.5 /spl mu/A-1.5 mA. The implant contains a single mixed analog/digital CMOS-ASIC for data synchronization and stimulus generation. Stimulation signals are applied via a monopolar intracochlear multielectrode array. Output capacitors are employed for safety reasons. A back-telemetry system for measuring electrode voltages and the implant supply voltage is incorporated. Data and power are transcutaneously transferred to the implant, using a single rf-channel. The overall data rate is 400 kb/s. >"
    }
  }
}